<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-518-825  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 518 825.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 15 1990 v24 n42 p73(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Options cloud cabling picture. (selection of cabling for networks)(Networking - Analysis)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wexler, Joanie M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local area network (LANs) cabling selection becomes morecomplicated as multivendor systems multiply.andP;  No longer canhardware selection be based simply on whether a LAN is to beEthernet (requiring coaxial cable) or Token Ring (and hence,twisted-pair).andP;  The number of options and combinations ofdifferent vendors' products means reviewing network installation,use and expansion for both the short- and the long-term.andP;  Cablingis a significant part of the per-user cost of installing anetwork, making the choice among plastic and glass fiber optic,coaxial, and twisted-pair cabling even more important.andP;  Newproducts provide connectivity across different kinds of cabling,enhancing flexibility but adding another layer of hardware.andO;High-speed data transmission and wireless LANs add to thecomplexity.andP;  Experts recommend, other things being equal, fiberoptic for the backbone and twisted-pair to the desktop nodes.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CablesLocal Area NetworksDecision MakingEquipment AcquisitionHardware SelectionTwisted PairCoaxial cablesFiber optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Annual growth rate for cabling types, worldwide shipments1987-1994. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>